{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d3726f1f-04c2-41cd-a787-14e29f3ab317","content":"This question is about general .NET/NativeAOT knowledge rather than anything in this repository. Here's the answer:\n\n**Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Check Apple's crash reporter** — macOS automatically saves crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** in your shell before running:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Core files land in `/cores/` (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n3. **Analyze with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is missing or empty**, ensure SIP isn't blocking core dumps and the `/cores` directory exists with write permissions:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n5. **For richer .NET diagnostics**, set the environment variable:\n   ```bash\n   export DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\n   export DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4   # Full dump\n   ```\n   (These rely on the runtime's built-in dump support, which may be limited in NativeAOT.)\n\nSince NativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump`, the OS-level core dump via `ulimit -c unlimited` + `/cores/` is your primary path on macOS.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"938a78a0-47ca-4794-adfe-dac73c865ff4","outputTokens":382,"requestId":"204D:39211A:73102E:8607C6:69F0128B"},"id":"4f7784f2-2f99-436a-90bd-2bf8392d2090","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:51:16.524Z","parentId":"6032f4e9-59cf-4cbc-9250-f048154a42e3"}
